ry |first1=Jason P. |title=Dave Matthews Band: Come Tomorrow |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/dave-matthews-band-come-tomorrow/ |website=Pitchfork |accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Modell |first1=Josh |title=Review: Dave Matthews Band's 'Come Tomorrow' Balances Sensitivity, Big-Tent Musicality |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/review-dave-matthews-bands-come-tomorrow-w520869 |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Come Tomorrow''''' is the ninth studio album by [[Dave Matthews Band]], and was released on June 8, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.davematthewsband.com/news/dave-matthews-bands-come-tomorrow-set-for-june-8-release-on-rca-records |title=Come Tomorrow announce date/}}</ref> The album is their first since 2012's ''[[Away from the World]].'' <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8379879/dave-matthews-announces-come-tomorrow-come-tomorrow-album|title=Dave Matthews Band Prepping 'Come Tomorrow' Album For June|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/dave-matthews-band-prep-new-lp-come-tomorrow-w519528|title=Dave Matthews Band Prep First LP in Six Years, 'Come Tomorrow'|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Recording==\nWorking between tours at studios in Seattle, Los Angeles and Charlottesville, Dave Matthews Band chose to record with several different producers, including John Alagia, Mark Batson, Rob Cavallo and Rob Evans.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://liveforlivemusic.com/news/dave-matthews-band-come-tomorrow-album/|title=Dave Matthews Band Announces First New Album Since 2012, 'Come Tomorrow', Due Out In June|date=2018-04-25|work=L4LM|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nNine of the 14 tracks on ''Come Tomorrow'' were played live prior to the official album announcement on April 25, 2018. \"Do You Remember\" was debuted at [[Farm Aid]] in 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dmbalmanac.com/TourShowSet.aspx?id=453072474 |title=DMBAlmanac.com\u00b2 |publisher=Dmbalmanac.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-20}}</ref> \"Again and Again\" appeared on DMB setlists in 2016 as \"Bob Law\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dmbalmanac.com/SongStats.aspx?sid=4874 |title=DMBAlmanac.com\u00b2 |publisher=Dmbalmanac.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-20}}</ref> \"Samurai Cop\" had been a regular at Dave solo, Dave & Tim acoustic and full band shows since 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dmbalmanac.com/SongStats.aspx?sid=4873 |title=DMBAlmanac.com\u00b2 |publisher=Dmbalmanac.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-20}}</ref> \"Here on Out\" was played live just once before the announcement and that came on the Seasons of Cuba [[PBS]]-televised special in 2016 with Dave being backed by the Chamber Orchestra of Havana.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://liveforlivemusic.com/news/watch-dave-matthews-perform-brand-new-song-called-lincoln-center/ |title=Dave Matthews Debuts New Song \"Here On Out\" With An Orchestra At Lincoln Center [Watch&#93; |publisher=Liveforlivemusic.com |date=2016-11-02 |accessdate=2018-06-20}}</ref> The band had regularly featured \"Black and Blue Bird\" and \"Virginia in the Rain\" at shows since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dmbalmanac.com/TourSongInfo.aspx?tid=128&where=2015 |title=DMBAlmanac.com\u00b2 |publisher=Dmbalmanac.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-20}}</ref>\n\nThe longest-tenured songs on the album are \"Can't Stop\" and \"Idea of You\", both of which had been in the band's rotation since 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dmbalmanac.com/TourSongInfo.aspx?tid=87&where=2006 |title=DMBAlmanac.com\u00b2 |publisher=Dmbalmanac.com |date= |accessdate=2018-06-20}}</ref> It was originally reported that \u201cCome On Come On\u201d was written in 2008, at an early session of the band's recording of [[Big Whiskey and the GrooGrux King]], but the October 2018 leak of \u201cThe Batson Sessions\u201d revealed that the song (previously titled \u201cCome On\u201d) was virtually unchanged from an April 2006 session with Mark Batson. An extended version of \"bkdkdkdd\" was previously performed live under the title \"Be Yourself\".\n\nThe cover art for the album is by B\u00e9atrice Coron.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Come Tomorrow'' debuted at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with 292,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s, making it the biggest sales week for a rock album in over four years, and the biggest sales week for an album in 2018, with 285,000 copies sold.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8461343/dave-matthews-band-come-tomorrow-billboard-200-no-1-album|title=Dave Matthews Band Scores Seventh No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Come Tomorrow'|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|magazine=Billboard|date=June 17, 2018|accessdate=June 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nThe track listing for the album was announced on May 2, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.davematthewsband.com/news/dave-matthews-band-reveals-track-listing-for-come-tomorrow/|title=Come Tomorrow track list announcement}}</ref>\n\nAll songs written by [[Dave Matthews|David J. Matthews]] except where noted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/come-tomorrow-mw0003173938/|title=Come Tomorrow - Dave Matthews Band|publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2018-06-09}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n|title1 = Samurai Cop (Oh Joy Begin)\n|length1 = 4:22\n|title2 = Can't Stop\n|writer2 = [[Mark Batson]], [[Carter Beauford]], [[Stefan Lessard]], Matthews, [[LeRoi Moore]], [[Boyd Tinsley]]\n|length2 = 4:43\n|title3 = Here on Out\n|length3 = 3:18\n|title4 = That Girl Is You\n|length4 = 3:16\n|title5 = She\n|writer5 = Matthews, [[John Alagia]]\n|length5 = 3:51\n|title6 = Idea of You\n|writer6 = Batson, Beauford, Lessard, Matthews, Moore, Tinsley\n|length6 = 4:44\n|title7 = Virginia in the Rain\n|writer7 = Beauford, Lessard, Matthews, Doug McKean\n|length7 = 6:09\n|title8 = Again and Again \n|length8 = 4:25\n|title9 = bkdkdkdd\n|length9 = 0:27\n|title10 = Black and Blue Bird\n|writer10 = [[Jeff Coffin]], Matthews, McKean, [[Rashawn Ross]]\n|length10 = 3:33\n|title11 = Come on Come On\n|writer11 = Matthews, Batson\n|length11 = 4:39\n|title12 = Do You Remember\n|length12 = 4:17\n|title13 = Come Tomorrow\n|writer13 = Matthews, Batson\n|length13 = 4:46\n|title14 = When I'm Weary\n|writer14 = Matthews, Batson\n|length14 = 1:56\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n'''Dave Matthews Band'''\n*[[Carter Beauford]] \u2013 drums, vocals\n*[[Jeff Coffin]] \u2013 saxophone\n*[[Stefan Lessard]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[Dave Matthews]] \u2013 acoustic and electric guitars, lead vocals\n*[[Tim Reynolds]] \u2013 electric guitar\n*[[Rashawn Ross]] \u2013 trumpet\n*[[LeRoi Moore]] \u2013 saxophone on \"Can't Stop\" and \"Idea of You\"\n\n'''Additional musicians'''\n*[[Brandi Carlile]] - backing vocals on \"Come Tomorrow\"\n*[[Mark Batson]] \u2013 piano on \"When I'm Weary\"\n*Buddy Strong \u2013 organ on \"Black and Blue Bird\"\n*[[Butch Taylor]] \u2013 piano on \"Can't Stop\", \"Come On Come On\", and \"Idea of You\"\n*[[Boyd Tinsley]] \u2013 violin on \"Idea of You\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.nytimes.com/2018/06/06/arts/music/dave-matthews-band-come-tomorrow-review.html|title=Dave Matthews Sings to the Next Generation on \u2018Come Tomorrow\u2019}}</ref>\n*[[Jerry Hey]] \u2013 horn arrangement on \"Samurai Cop (Oh Joy Begin)\" and \"Again and Again\"\n*[[David Campbell (composer)|David Campbell]] \u2013 string arrangement on \"Here On Out\" and \"Again and Again\"\n*[[Rob Cavallo]] \u2013 organ on \"Samurai Cop (Oh Joy Begin)\", electric piano on \"bkdkdkdd\"\n\n'''Production'''\n* Producer \u2013 [[John Alag\u00eda]], [[Mark Batson]], [[Rob Cavallo]], Rob Evans\n*Engineer \u2013 Andrew Ching, Andy Park, Doug McKean, Julian Anderson, Matt Dyson, Rob Evans, Tom Rasulo, [[Steven Miller (record producer)|Steven Miller]], Wesley Seidman, Aaron Fessel, [[John Alag\u00eda]], Chris Kress, Pedro Calloni, Jason Shavey, Sean Quackenbush\n*Mixing engineer \u2013 [[John Alag\u00eda]], Rob Evans, Doug McKean, Billy Centenaro\n*Mastering engineer \u2013 [[Brad Blackwood]]\n*Executive producer \u2013 [[John Alag\u00eda]]\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2018\u201319)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCanada|2|artist=Dave Matthews Band|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 19, 2018}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Netherlands|24|artist=Dave Matthews Band|album=Come Tomorrow|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand Heatseeker Albums ([[Recorded Music NZ|RMNZ]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4488|title=NZ Heatseeker Albums Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n| 5\n|-\n{{album chart|Poland|49|id=1191|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Portugal|42|artist=Dave Matthews Band|album=Come Tomorrow|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 1, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Switzerland|42|artist=Dave Matthews Band|album=Come Tomorrow|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 20, 2018}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"BB200\"/>\n| 1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2018)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US ''Billboard'' 200<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2018/top-billboard-200-albums|title=Billboard 200 Albums \u2013 Year-End 2018|work=Billboard|accessdate=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n| 95\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Davematthewsband}}\n\n[[Category:2018 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums pr